726227f-a.title: Queens: Broadway - Justice Avenue
726227f-a.text:
Broadway, east side, between Justice Avenue and Queens Boulevard,
showing an old building which was known as the Welter Building. It
was owned by one Schneller in 1891.
July 2, 1935
P. L. Sperr
NO REPRODICTIONS

726228f-a.title: Queens: Broadway - Justice Avenue
726228f-a.text:
Broadway, at the S. E. corner of Justice Avenue, showing the
110th Precinct police station and courthouse, formerly known as
the Town Hall of Newtown. It was erected in 1891.
View 1: June 7, 1927
View 2: July 21, 1935
P. L. Sperr
NO REPRODUTTIONS

726229f-b.title: Queens: Broadway - Justice Avenue
726229f-b.text:
Broadway, west side, north from Justice Avenue, to Maurice
Avenue, showing four views of ar original section of the town
of Newtown. Views one ard two show at the right the formcr
St. James Episcopal Church, now used as a chapel. The houes
seen in these two views were the propertv of S. Manwaring in 1873.
View number two also shows adjoining and next to the Exerpt
Firemen 's Association Home, at the left, the old and new quarters
of the Newtown Pegister. This old one story structre was the
first school erected In the village. It was built in 17dO and
consisted of one room. It was used as a school until 1870. White
purchased the builjing in 1873 when he founded tne Register. Og
all the buildinos seen in the four views only the chanel remained
in Octoser 1930, ard the building ad joinirg it. In view number four
center right, is the building housing the Buckley Butcher Shop.
TNe Exempt Firemen 's Buiiding was formerly a one story structure
which was enlarged some time subsequent to 1843 when the Wandewenock
Company was organized.
1922
Views 1,E and 4
View 3: October 1982.
